\title{Peer Review}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Systematic peer review toolkit. Evaluate methodology, statistics, design, reproducibility, ethics, figure integrity, reporting standards, for manuscript and grant review across disciplines."}

\subtree{
\title{Scientific Critical Evaluation and Peer Review}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Peer review is a systematic process for evaluating scientific manuscripts. Assess methodology, statistics, design, reproducibility, ethics, and reporting standards. Apply this skill for manuscript and grant review across disciplines with constructive, rigorous evaluation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when:}

\ul{
\li{Conducting peer review of scientific manuscripts for journals}
\li{Evaluating grant proposals and research applications}
\li{Assessing methodology and experimental design rigor}
\li{Reviewing statistical analyses and reporting standards}
\li{Evaluating reproducibility and data availability}
\li{Checking compliance with reporting guidelines (CONSORT, STROBE, PRISMA)}
\li{Providing constructive feedback on scientific writing}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Visual Enhancement with Scientific Schematics}
\p{\strong{When creating documents with this skill, always consider adding scientific diagrams and schematics to enhance visual communication.}}

\p{If your document does not already contain schematics or diagrams:}

\ul{
\li{Use the \strong{scientific-schematics} skill to generate AI-powered publication-quality diagrams}
\li{Simply describe your desired diagram in natural language}
\li{Nano Banana Pro will automatically generate, review, and refine the schematic}
}

\p{\strong{For new documents:} Scientific schematics should be generated by default to visually represent key concepts, workflows, architectures, or relationships described in the text.}

\p{\strong{How to generate schematics:}}

\pre{\startverb
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "your diagram description" -o figures/output.png
\stopverb}

\p{The AI will automatically:}

\ul{
\li{Create publication-quality images with proper formatting}
\li{Review and refine through multiple iterations}
\li{Ensure accessibility (colorblind-friendly, high contrast)}
\li{Save outputs in the figures/ directory}
}

\p{\strong{When to add schematics:}}

\ul{
\li{Peer review workflow diagrams}
\li{Evaluation criteria decision trees}
\li{Review process flowcharts}
\li{Methodology assessment frameworks}
\li{Quality assessment visualizations}
\li{Reporting guidelines compliance diagrams}
\li{Any complex concept that benefits from visualization}
}

\p{For detailed guidance on creating schematics, refer to the scientific-schematics skill documentation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Peer Review Workflow}
\p{Conduct peer review systematically through the following stages, adapting depth and focus based on the manuscript type and discipline.}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 1: Initial Assessment}
\p{Begin with a high-level evaluation to determine the manuscript's scope, novelty, and overall quality.}

\p{\strong{Key Questions:}}

\ul{
\li{What is the central research question or hypothesis?}
\li{What are the main findings and conclusions?}
\li{Is the work scientifically sound and significant?}
\li{Is the work appropriate for the intended venue?}
\li{Are there any immediate major flaws that would preclude publication?}
}

\p{\strong{Output:} Brief summary (2-3 sentences) capturing the manuscript's essence and initial impression.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 2: Detailed Section-by-Section Review}
\p{Conduct a thorough evaluation of each manuscript section, documenting specific concerns and strengths.}

\subtree{
\title{Abstract and Title}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Accuracy:} Does the abstract accurately reflect the study's content and conclusions?}
\li{\strong{Clarity:} Is the title specific, accurate, and informative?}
\li{\strong{Completeness:} Are key findings and methods summarized appropriately?}
\li{\strong{Accessibility:} Is the abstract comprehensible to a broad scientific audience?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Introduction}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Context:} Is the background information adequate and current?}
\li{\strong{Rationale:} Is the research question clearly motivated and justified?}
\li{\strong{Novelty:} Is the work's originality and significance clearly articulated?}
\li{\strong{Literature:} Are relevant prior studies appropriately cited?}
\li{\strong{Objectives:} Are research aims/hypotheses clearly stated?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Methods}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Reproducibility:} Can another researcher replicate the study from the description provided?}
\li{\strong{Rigor:} Are the methods appropriate for addressing the research questions?}
\li{\strong{Detail:} Are protocols, reagents, equipment, and parameters sufficiently described?}
\li{\strong{Ethics:} Are ethical approvals, consent, and data handling properly documented?}
\li{\strong{Statistics:} Are statistical methods appropriate, clearly described, and justified?}
\li{\strong{Validation:} Are controls, replicates, and validation approaches adequate?}
}

\p{\strong{Critical elements to verify:}}

\ul{
\li{Sample sizes and power calculations}
\li{Randomization and blinding procedures}
\li{Inclusion/exclusion criteria}
\li{Data collection protocols}
\li{Computational methods and software versions}
\li{Statistical tests and correction for multiple comparisons}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Results}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Presentation:} Are results presented logically and clearly?}
\li{\strong{Figures/Tables:} Are visualizations appropriate, clear, and properly labeled?}
\li{\strong{Statistics:} Are statistical results properly reported (effect sizes, confidence intervals, p-values)?}
\li{\strong{Objectivity:} Are results presented without over-interpretation?}
\li{\strong{Completeness:} Are all relevant results included, including negative results?}
\li{\strong{Reproducibility:} Are raw data or summary statistics provided?}
}

\p{\strong{Common issues to identify:}}

\ul{
\li{Selective reporting of results}
\li{Inappropriate statistical tests}
\li{Missing error bars or measures of variability}
\li{Over-fitting or circular analysis}
\li{Batch effects or confounding variables}
\li{Missing controls or validation experiments}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Discussion}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Interpretation:} Are conclusions supported by the data?}
\li{\strong{Limitations:} Are study limitations acknowledged and discussed?}
\li{\strong{Context:} Are findings placed appropriately within existing literature?}
\li{\strong{Speculation:} Is speculation clearly distinguished from data-supported conclusions?}
\li{\strong{Significance:} Are implications and importance clearly articulated?}
\li{\strong{Future directions:} Are next steps or unanswered questions discussed?}
}

\p{\strong{Red flags:}}

\ul{
\li{Overstated conclusions}
\li{Ignoring contradictory evidence}
\li{Causal claims from correlational data}
\li{Inadequate discussion of limitations}
\li{Mechanistic claims without mechanistic evidence}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{References}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Completeness:} Are key relevant papers cited?}
\li{\strong{Currency:} Are recent important studies included?}
\li{\strong{Balance:} Are contrary viewpoints appropriately cited?}
\li{\strong{Accuracy:} Are citations accurate and appropriate?}
\li{\strong{Self-citation:} Is there excessive or inappropriate self-citation?}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 3: Methodological and Statistical Rigor}
\p{Evaluate the technical quality and rigor of the research with particular attention to common pitfalls.}

\p{\strong{Statistical Assessment:}}

\ul{
\li{Are statistical assumptions met (normality, independence, homoscedasticity)?}
\li{Are effect sizes reported alongside p-values?}
\li{Is multiple testing correction applied appropriately?}
\li{Are confidence intervals provided?}
\li{Is sample size justified with power analysis?}
\li{Are parametric vs. non-parametric tests chosen appropriately?}
\li{Are missing data handled properly?}
\li{Are exploratory vs. confirmatory analyses distinguished?}
}

\p{\strong{Experimental Design:}}

\ul{
\li{Are controls appropriate and adequate?}
\li{Is replication sufficient (biological and technical)?}
\li{Are potential confounders identified and controlled?}
\li{Is randomization properly implemented?}
\li{Are blinding procedures adequate?}
\li{Is the experimental design optimal for the research question?}
}

\p{\strong{Computational/Bioinformatics:}}

\ul{
\li{Are computational methods clearly described and justified?}
\li{Are software versions and parameters documented?}
\li{Is code made available for reproducibility?}
\li{Are algorithms and models validated appropriately?}
\li{Are assumptions of computational methods met?}
\li{Is batch correction applied appropriately?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 4: Reproducibility and Transparency}
\p{Assess whether the research meets modern standards for reproducibility and open science.}

\p{\strong{Data Availability:}}

\ul{
\li{Are raw data deposited in appropriate repositories?}
\li{Are accession numbers provided for public databases?}
\li{Are data sharing restrictions justified (e.g., patient privacy)?}
\li{Are data formats standard and accessible?}
}

\p{\strong{Code and Materials:}}

\ul{
\li{Is analysis code made available (GitHub, Zenodo, etc.)?}
\li{Are unique materials available or described sufficiently for recreation?}
\li{Are protocols detailed in sufficient depth?}
}

\p{\strong{Reporting Standards:}}

\ul{
\li{Does the manuscript follow discipline-specific reporting guidelines (CONSORT, PRISMA, ARRIVE, MIAME, MINSEQE, etc.)?}
\li{See \code{\startverb references/reporting_standards.md\stopverb} for common guidelines}
\li{Are all elements of the appropriate checklist addressed?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 5: Figure and Data Presentation}
\p{Evaluate the quality, clarity, and integrity of data visualization.}

\p{\strong{Quality Checks:}}

\ul{
\li{Are figures high resolution and clearly labeled?}
\li{Are axes properly labeled with units?}
\li{Are error bars defined (SD, SEM, CI)?}
\li{Are statistical significance indicators explained?}
\li{Are color schemes appropriate and accessible (colorblind-friendly)?}
\li{Are scale bars included for images?}
\li{Is data visualization appropriate for the data type?}
}

\p{\strong{Integrity Checks:}}

\ul{
\li{Are there signs of image manipulation (duplications, splicing)?}
\li{Are Western blots and gels appropriately presented?}
\li{Are representative images truly representative?}
\li{Are all conditions shown (no selective presentation)?}
}

\p{\strong{Clarity:}}

\ul{
\li{Can figures stand alone with their legends?}
\li{Is the message of each figure immediately clear?}
\li{Are there redundant figures or panels?}
\li{Would data be better presented as tables or figures?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 6: Ethical Considerations}
\p{Verify that the research meets ethical standards and guidelines.}

\p{\strong{Human Subjects:}}

\ul{
\li{Is IRB/ethics approval documented?}
\li{Is informed consent described?}
\li{Are vulnerable populations appropriately protected?}
\li{Is patient privacy adequately protected?}
\li{Are potential conflicts of interest disclosed?}
}

\p{\strong{Animal Research:}}

\ul{
\li{Is IACUC or equivalent approval documented?}
\li{Are procedures humane and justified?}
\li{Are the 3Rs (replacement, reduction, refinement) considered?}
\li{Are euthanasia methods appropriate?}
}

\p{\strong{Research Integrity:}}

\ul{
\li{Are there concerns about data fabrication or falsification?}
\li{Is authorship appropriate and justified?}
\li{Are competing interests disclosed?}
\li{Is funding source disclosed?}
\li{Are there concerns about plagiarism or duplicate publication?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stage 7: Writing Quality and Clarity}
\p{Assess the manuscript's clarity, organization, and accessibility.}

\p{\strong{Structure and Organization:}}

\ul{
\li{Is the manuscript logically organized?}
\li{Do sections flow coherently?}
\li{Are transitions between ideas clear?}
\li{Is the narrative compelling and clear?}
}

\p{\strong{Writing Quality:}}

\ul{
\li{Is the language clear, precise, and concise?}
\li{Are jargon and acronyms minimized and defined?}
\li{Is grammar and spelling correct?}
\li{Are sentences unnecessarily complex?}
\li{Is the passive voice overused?}
}

\p{\strong{Accessibility:}}

\ul{
\li{Can a non-specialist understand the main findings?}
\li{Are technical terms explained?}
\li{Is the significance clear to a broad audience?}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Structuring Peer Review Reports}
\p{Organize feedback in a hierarchical structure that prioritizes issues and provides actionable guidance.}

\subtree{
\title{Summary Statement}
\p{Provide a concise overall assessment (1-2 paragraphs):}

\ul{
\li{Brief synopsis of the research}
\li{Overall recommendation (accept, minor revisions, major revisions, reject)}
\li{Key strengths (2-3 bullet points)}
\li{Key weaknesses (2-3 bullet points)}
\li{Bottom-line assessment of significance and soundness}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Major Comments}
\p{List critical issues that significantly impact the manuscript's validity, interpretability, or significance. Number these sequentially for easy reference.}

\p{\strong{Major comments typically include:}}

\ul{
\li{Fundamental methodological flaws}
\li{Inappropriate statistical analyses}
\li{Unsupported or overstated conclusions}
\li{Missing critical controls or experiments}
\li{Serious reproducibility concerns}
\li{Major gaps in literature coverage}
\li{Ethical concerns}
}

\p{\strong{For each major comment:}}

\ol{
\li{Clearly state the issue}
\li{Explain why it's problematic}
\li{Suggest specific solutions or additional experiments}
\li{Indicate if addressing it is essential for publication}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Minor Comments}
\p{List less critical issues that would improve clarity, completeness, or presentation. Number these sequentially.}

\p{\strong{Minor comments typically include:}}

\ul{
\li{Unclear figure labels or legends}
\li{Missing methodological details}
\li{Typographical or grammatical errors}
\li{Suggestions for improved data presentation}
\li{Minor statistical reporting issues}
\li{Supplementary analyses that would strengthen conclusions}
\li{Requests for clarification}
}

\p{\strong{For each minor comment:}}

\ol{
\li{Identify the specific location (section, paragraph, figure)}
\li{State the issue clearly}
\li{Suggest how to address it}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Specific Line-by-Line Comments (Optional)}
\p{For manuscripts requiring detailed feedback, provide section-specific or line-by-line comments:}

\ul{
\li{Reference specific page/line numbers or sections}
\li{Note factual errors, unclear statements, or missing citations}
\li{Suggest specific edits for clarity}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Questions for Authors}
\p{List specific questions that need clarification:}

\ul{
\li{Methodological details that are unclear}
\li{Seemingly contradictory results}
\li{Missing information needed to evaluate the work}
\li{Requests for additional data or analyses}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tone and Approach}
\p{Maintain a constructive, professional, and collegial tone throughout the review.}

\p{\strong{Best Practices:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Be constructive:} Frame criticism as opportunities for improvement}
\li{\strong{Be specific:} Provide concrete examples and actionable suggestions}
\li{\strong{Be balanced:} Acknowledge strengths as well as weaknesses}
\li{\strong{Be respectful:} Remember that authors have invested significant effort}
\li{\strong{Be objective:} Focus on the science, not the scientists}
\li{\strong{Be thorough:} Don't overlook issues, but prioritize appropriately}
\li{\strong{Be clear:} Avoid ambiguous or vague criticism}
}

\p{\strong{Avoid:}}

\ul{
\li{Personal attacks or dismissive language}
\li{Sarcasm or condescension}
\li{Vague criticism without specific examples}
\li{Requesting unnecessary experiments beyond the scope}
\li{Demanding adherence to personal preferences vs. best practices}
\li{Revealing your identity if reviewing is double-blind}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Special Considerations by Manuscript Type}
\subtree{
\title{Original Research Articles}
\ul{
\li{Emphasize rigor, reproducibility, and novelty}
\li{Assess significance and impact}
\li{Verify that conclusions are data-driven}
\li{Check for complete methods and appropriate controls}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Reviews and Meta-Analyses}
\ul{
\li{Evaluate comprehensiveness of literature coverage}
\li{Assess search strategy and inclusion/exclusion criteria}
\li{Verify systematic approach and lack of bias}
\li{Check for critical analysis vs. mere summarization}
\li{For meta-analyses, evaluate statistical approach and heterogeneity}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Methods Papers}
\ul{
\li{Emphasize validation and comparison to existing methods}
\li{Assess reproducibility and availability of protocols/code}
\li{Evaluate improvements over existing approaches}
\li{Check for sufficient detail for implementation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Short Reports/Letters}
\ul{
\li{Adapt expectations for brevity}
\li{Ensure core findings are still rigorous and significant}
\li{Verify that format is appropriate for findings}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Preprints}
\ul{
\li{Recognize that these have not undergone formal peer review}
\li{May be less polished than journal submissions}
\li{Still apply rigorous standards for scientific validity}
\li{Consider providing constructive feedback to help authors improve before journal submission}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Presentations and Slide Decks}
\p{\strong{⚠️ CRITICAL: For presentations, NEVER read the PDF directly. ALWAYS convert to images first.}}

\p{When reviewing scientific presentations (PowerPoint, Beamer, slide decks):}

\subtree{
\title{Mandatory Image-Based Review Workflow}
\p{\strong{NEVER attempt to read presentation PDFs directly} - this causes buffer overflow errors and doesn't show visual formatting issues.}

\p{\strong{Required Process:}}

\ol{
\li{Convert PDF to images using Python:}
\li{Read and inspect EACH slide image file sequentially}
\li{Document issues with specific slide numbers}
\li{Provide feedback on visual formatting and content}
}

\p{\strong{Print when starting review:}}

\pre{\startverb
[HH:MM:SS] PEER REVIEW: Presentation detected - converting to images for review
[HH:MM:SS] PDF REVIEW: NEVER reading PDF directly - using image-based inspection
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Presentation-Specific Evaluation Criteria}
\p{\strong{Visual Design and Readability:}}

\ul{
\li{[ ] Text is large enough (minimum 18pt, ideally 24pt+ for body text)}
\li{[ ] High contrast between text and background (4.5:1 minimum, 7:1 preferred)}
\li{[ ] Color scheme is professional and colorblind-accessible}
\li{[ ] Consistent visual design across all slides}
\li{[ ] White space is adequate (not cramped)}
\li{[ ] Fonts are clear and professional}
}

\p{\strong{Layout and Formatting (Check EVERY Slide Image):}}

\ul{
\li{[ ] No text overflow or truncation at slide edges}
\li{[ ] No element overlaps (text over images, overlapping shapes)}
\li{[ ] Titles are consistently positioned}
\li{[ ] Content is properly aligned}
\li{[ ] Bullets and text are not cut off}
\li{[ ] Figures fit within slide boundaries}
\li{[ ] Captions and labels are visible and readable}
}

\p{\strong{Content Quality:}}

\ul{
\li{[ ] One main idea per slide (not overloaded)}
\li{[ ] Minimal text (3-6 bullets per slide maximum)}
\li{[ ] Bullet points are concise (5-7 words each)}
\li{[ ] Figures are simplified and clear (not copy-pasted from papers)}
\li{[ ] Data visualizations have large, readable labels}
\li{[ ] Citations are present and properly formatted}
\li{\startverb [ ] Results/data slides dominate the presentation (40-50% of content)\stopverb}
}

\p{\strong{Structure and Flow:}}

\ul{
\li{[ ] Clear narrative arc (introduction → methods → results → discussion)}
\li{[ ] Logical progression between slides}
\li{[ ] Slide count appropriate for talk duration (~1 slide per minute)}
\li{[ ] Title slide includes authors, affiliation, date}
\li{[ ] Introduction cites relevant background literature (3-5 papers)}
\li{[ ] Discussion cites comparison papers (3-5 papers)}
\li{[ ] Conclusions slide summarizes key findings}
\li{[ ] Acknowledgments/funding slide at end}
}

\p{\strong{Scientific Content:}}

\ul{
\li{[ ] Research question clearly stated}
\li{[ ] Methods adequately summarized (not excessive detail)}
\li{[ ] Results presented logically with clear visualizations}
\li{[ ] Statistical significance indicated appropriately}
\li{[ ] Conclusions supported by data shown}
\li{[ ] Limitations acknowledged where appropriate}
\li{[ ] Future directions or broader impact discussed}
}

\p{\strong{Common Presentation Issues to Flag:}}

\p{\strong{Critical Issues (Must Fix):}}

\ul{
\li{Text overflow making content unreadable}
\li{Font sizes too small (<18pt)}
\li{Element overlaps obscuring data}
\li{Insufficient contrast (text hard to read)}
\li{Figures too complex or illegible}
\li{No citations (completely unsupported claims)}
\li{Slide count drastically mismatched to duration}
}

\p{\strong{Major Issues (Should Fix):}}

\ul{
\li{Inconsistent design across slides}
\li{Too much text (walls of text, not bullets)}
\li{Poorly simplified figures (axis labels too small)}
\li{Cramped layout with insufficient white space}
\li{Missing key structural elements (no conclusion slide)}
\li{Poor color choices (not colorblind-safe)}
\li{\startverb Minimal results content (<30% of slides)\stopverb}
}

\p{\strong{Minor Issues (Suggestions for Improvement):}}

\ul{
\li{Could use more visuals/diagrams}
\li{Some slides slightly text-heavy}
\li{Minor alignment inconsistencies}
\li{Could benefit from more white space}
\li{Additional citations would strengthen claims}
\li{Color scheme could be more modern}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Review Report Format for Presentations}
\p{\strong{Summary Statement:}}

\ul{
\li{Overall impression of presentation quality}
\li{Appropriateness for target audience and duration}
\li{Key strengths (visual design, content, clarity)}
\li{Key weaknesses (formatting issues, content gaps)}
\li{Recommendation (ready to present, minor revisions, major revisions)}
}

\p{\strong{Layout and Formatting Issues (By Slide Number):}}

\pre{\startverb
Slide 3: Text overflow - bullet point 4 extends beyond right margin
Slide 7: Element overlap - figure overlaps with caption text
Slide 12: Font size - axis labels too small to read from distance
Slide 18: Alignment - title not centered
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Content and Structure Feedback:}}

\ul{
\li{Adequacy of background context and citations}
\li{Clarity of research question and objectives}
\li{Quality of methods summary}
\li{Effectiveness of results presentation}
\li{Strength of conclusions and implications}
}

\p{\strong{Design and Accessibility:}}

\ul{
\li{Overall visual appeal and professionalism}
\li{Color contrast and readability}
\li{Colorblind accessibility}
\li{Consistency across slides}
}

\p{\strong{Timing and Scope:}}

\ul{
\li{Whether slide count matches intended duration}
\li{Appropriate level of detail for talk type}
\li{Balance between sections}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example Image-Based Review Process}
\pre{\startverb
[14:30:00] PEER REVIEW: Starting review of presentation
[14:30:05] PEER REVIEW: Presentation detected - converting to images
[14:30:10] PDF REVIEW: Running pdf_to_images.py on presentation.pdf
[14:30:15] PDF REVIEW: Converted 25 slides to images in review/ directory
[14:30:20] PDF REVIEW: Inspecting slide 1/25 - title slide
[14:30:25] PDF REVIEW: Inspecting slide 2/25 - introduction
...
[14:35:40] PDF REVIEW: Inspecting slide 25/25 - acknowledgments
[14:35:45] PDF REVIEW: Completed image-based review
[14:35:50] PEER REVIEW: Found 8 layout issues, 3 content issues
[14:35:55] PEER REVIEW: Generating structured feedback by slide number
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Remember:} For presentations, the visual inspection via images is MANDATORY. Never attempt to read presentation PDFs as text - it will fail and miss all visual formatting issues.}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Resources}
\p{This skill includes reference materials to support comprehensive peer review:}

\subtree{
\title{references/reporting_standards.md}
\p{Guidelines for major reporting standards across disciplines (CONSORT, PRISMA, ARRIVE, MIAME, STROBE, etc.) to evaluate completeness of methods and results reporting.}
}

\subtree{
\title{references/common_issues.md}
\p{Catalog of frequent methodological and statistical issues encountered in peer review, with guidance on identifying and addressing them.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Final Checklist}
\p{Before finalizing the review, verify:}

\ul{
\li{[ ] Summary statement clearly conveys overall assessment}
\li{[ ] Major concerns are clearly identified and justified}
\li{[ ] Suggested revisions are specific and actionable}
\li{[ ] Minor issues are noted but properly categorized}
\li{[ ] Statistical methods have been evaluated}
\li{[ ] Reproducibility and data availability assessed}
\li{[ ] Ethical considerations verified}
\li{[ ] Figures and tables evaluated for quality and integrity}
\li{[ ] Writing quality assessed}
\li{[ ] Tone is constructive and professional throughout}
\li{[ ] Review is thorough but proportionate to manuscript scope}
\li{[ ] Recommendation is consistent with identified issues}
}
}
}